{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/understanding-combinatorics-number-of-paths-on-a-grid-bddf08e28384", "time": 1683005625.758989, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/understanding-combinatorics-number-of-paths-on-a-grid-bddf08e28384/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Understanding Combinatorics: Number of Paths on a Grid | by Branislav Holl\u00e4nder | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Understanding Combinatorics: Number of Paths on a Grid", "description": "Basic combinatorics is an indispensable tool at the disposal of any person programming, be it a developer, an AI expert, or a data scientist. Suppose that we want to get from the orange to the green\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [], "all_paragraphs": ["Basic combinatorics is an indispensable tool at the disposal of any person programming, be it a developer, an AI expert, or a data scientist.", "In this article, we will solve a simple combinatorial problem: counting the number of paths from one corner of a general WxH grid to the other.", "Let\u2019s start out by looking at this 3x3 grid:", "Suppose that we want to get from the orange to the green square. Each step we may move right or down. We will denote the move to the right by R and the move down by D. We are interested in the number of distinct paths we can take. Let us enumerate the paths by hand:", "We can conclude that there are 6 distinct paths in this grid. Now take a look at this 8x8 grid:", "If you try to count the number of paths on this grid, if will take you quite some time. We will need some more intelligent, mathematical approach. First note that the number of steps we have to take doesn\u2019t depend on the path taken.", "The distance, measured in steps, is always the same.", "This distance is also called L1 distance, city block distance or Manhattan distance, due to the square-shaped blocks in New York\u2019s downtown.", "On the other hand, we notice that on a square grid, the number of R moves has to equal the number of D moves because of the symmetry. Furthermore, we need 7+7=14 steps in every path (you can that easily by moving along the border of the grid). These two requirements make it possible to redefine the problem for the 8x8 grid in the following way:", "Find the number of distinct permutations of the string RRRRRRRDDDDDDD.", "Now, the number of permutations is in general defined by N! or N*(N-1)*(N-2)*\u2026*2, otherwise known as the factorial. Hereby, N is the length of the string. In our case, 14! = 87178291200. However, we have to account for the fact that the order of the R\u2019s and D\u2019s doesn\u2019t matter; they are the same. The number of the different permutations of both is 7! = 5040. We have to count the number twice since both the R\u2019s and D\u2019s are indistinguishable from each other. In other words, we divide 14! by 7!*7!. This gives us 3432, which is the correct answer.", "To generalize our formula for any NxN grid, we can write:", "Incidentally, there is an easier way to write this: the number D = N! / (K! * (N-K)!) is also called the binomial coefficient and we can write (N choose K). This number denotes the number of ways we can pick K objects from a bag of N objects, regardless of the picking order. Therefore, we can also write our formula as:", "What about a more general WxH grid? In this case, the number of steps is (W-1) * (H-1) and we have to choose (W-1) R moves (you can check that yourself). Therefore, the formula becomes:", "Easy, right? Now notice that instead of choosing (W-1) R moves, we could have chosen (H-1) D moves. Intuitively, this should give us the same answer, and it does. In other words, this means that the binomial coefficient is symmetric:", "As an exercise, try to count the number of paths on a 30x20 or even 99x99 grid. You could also try to write a program that recursively counts all the paths, however such a program could take very long to finish on a 99x99 grid!", "I hope that you learned some practical combinatorics in this post and that you will be motivated to learn more about this fascinating subject.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "AI | Software Development | Other Crazy Interests"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Fbddf08e28384&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Funderstanding-combinatorics-number-of-paths-on-a-grid-bddf08e28384&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Funderstanding-combinatorics-number-of-paths-on-a-grid-bddf08e28384&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Funderstanding-combinatorics-number-of-paths-on-a-grid-bddf08e28384&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Funderstanding-combinatorics-number-of-paths-on-a-grid-bddf08e28384&source=post_page---two_column_layou